<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-06-29T21:41:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-06-29T21:41:00-05:00" n="1157" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1157">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.6363/117.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">Consul <persName type="from">Miller</persName> to the
                                    <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Consulate</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Tampico</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-06-29T20:00:00-06:41">
                                    <hi rend="italic">June 29, 1914, 8 p.m.</hi>
                                </date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>General Cándido Aguilar informed this office today that he had given
                            orders for proper protection Panuco-Topila district and that all
                            Americans who have requested permission to carry revolvers have been
                            granted same. Also that he will severely punish any disorders or
                            molestation of workingmen. Admiral Mayo called on Acting Governor Lara
                            this morning and Governor Lara promised to send some troops to Panuco
                            pending arrival troops of General Aguilar. Authorities manifest
                            disposition to give necessary protection.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Miller</hi></signed>.</closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>